<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister on Implementing New Currency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister on Implementing New Currency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0305194094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 2 
May 94 p 10 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0305194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Sao Paulo - After visiting the 20th Century 
Brazilian biennial art exhibit in Sao Paulo yesterday, Finance 
Minister Rubens Ricupero said "the real will begin circulating 
even before approval of the provisional measure, which will be 
reedited as many times as necessary." Ricupero said the text 
will include the salary adjustment measures that were negotiated 
with Congress. 
  The minister said the new text sets forth that the 
government 
will compensate any salary loss caused by the conversion into 
URV's [Real Value Units]. He reiterated that the president will 
"shortly" announce the implementation of the new currency, but 
he did not specify the date. The minister said the period 
between the announcement and the implementation of the new 
currency can be longer than the 35 days provided for by the 
provisional measure. Ricupero said the provisional measure that 
creates the real has not yet been drawn up. He said: "This will 
follow the presidential announcement." 
  The minister said he does not believe the rural bloc will 
impede approval of the provisional measure again. "The bloc is 
not that big, there has been some exaggeration," he said, adding 
that the provisional measure should be approved in May, with the 
support of other parties. "Even if it is not approved, it will 
not delay the implementation of the real," he said, pointing out 
that the measure can be reedited an unspecified number of times. 
"Provisional measures operate as laws and come into force as of 
the time they are submitted to Congress," he explained. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

