<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lula's Plan To Form `Bloc of Debtor Countries' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lula's Plan To Form `Bloc of Debtor Countries' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0305193794 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 2 
May 94 p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0305193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luis Inacio Lula da Silva plans to lead a bloc of 
debtor countries to negotiate with creditors. In his first news 
conference as an official candidate, Lula said that, if elected, 
he will seek to form a bloc of poor countries and noted that he 
would only break relations with the IMF if creditors are 
intransigent. He added: "One cannot discuss social issues with 
the IMF managing director." 
  Upon closing the 9th Workers Party [PT] convention, Lula 
resigned as PT president. He was replaced by Deputy Rui Falcao, 
a member of PT radical group, who was elected in return for the 
radical groups' agreement to withdraw their proposal for a debt 
moratorium from the PT platform. Lula then canceled a rally 
following the death of car racer Ayrton Senna. 
  Lula said he does not fear capital flight from the country 
if 
he is elected president because "there has always been capital 
flight here." He believes the final version of the PT program 
shows rich countries that the PT "is aware of the responsibility 
entailed in ruling a country as important as Brazil, which needs 
to adopt a political position in keeping with its standing, and 
thus prevent it from being treated as a mere exporter of kiwi 
fruits." Euphoric over his victory over PT radicals, Lula said 
the PT remains united and that "the war predicted by the press 
prior to the convention never took place." 

</TEXT>

