<H3> <TI>   Castro: Decree To Confiscate Illegally Gained Property </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Castro: Decree To Confiscate Illegally Gained Property </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0205184094 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1748 GMT 2 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0205184094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 2 May (PL) -- Today, Cuban President Fidel 
Castro announced that the measures to strengthen the country's 
domestic finances began this week with a fight against 
individuals who become rich illegally. The president said he is 
already drafting a decree to confiscate illegally acquired 
property [words indistinct] in an expedited and noncomplicated 
manner. 
  Castro said the government will not rest for a single moment 
in applying the measures, which the Cuban parliament decided to 
implement today following a two-day debate and an extensive 
consultation of the people during the first three months of the 
year. He said all the decisions cannot be implemented together 
because they need to be put in order. 
  The fight against those who become rich illegally here, 
called "profiteers," was one of the primary demands in more than 
80,000 consultations convened by labor unions, in which 
approximately 3 million workers participated. 
  The purpose of this process, dubbed here "workers 
parliaments," was to learn about the people's opinions on needed 
measures to face the country's current crisis caused by the U.S. 
blockade and the loss of traditional trade relations following 
the disappearance of the European Socialist Bloc. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

