<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Foreign Minister Heads Special UN Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Foreign Minister Heads Special UN Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0305045894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1838 GMT 2 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0305045894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bridgetown, 2 May (PL) -- Today, Fernando Ramirez de 
Estenoz, Cuban ambassador to the United Nations and first 
foreign relations vice minister, begins heading a UN mission 
before the World Conference of Small Island States meeting in 
Barbados. 
  Ramirez de Estenoz told PRENSA LATINA that Cuba was selected 
to preside over a special group, including Syria, Tunisia, and a 
UN official, to negotiate in the name of the UN's decolonization 
committee at the Bridgetown session. "It has to do with 
consulations on a very important and delicate topic, dealing 
with the colonial status of some member-countries of the 
alliance of small island states," the diplomat said. 
  Of the 41 members of the alliance, known as AOSIS, nearly 
one-fifth still maintain a colonial status. In the Caribbean, 
French overseas territories (Martinique and Guadeloupe), 
Montserrat, Anguila, Bermuda, Turks and Caicos, and the Virgin 
Islands have not yet gained independence. 
  One of the problems that makes the UN decolonization 
committee's work difficult is that in most of these territories, 
under colonial tutelage economic development prospects, future 
independence is unfavorable in the current international 
situation. 
  In Anguila and Bermuda, several plebiscites have resulted in 
majority votes against independence because the population 
considers survival in these small states unlikely without 
financial backing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

