<H3> <TI>   Assembly Committee Reviews Bill on Various Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assembly Committee Reviews Bill on Various Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0105192294 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0058 GMT 1 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0105192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 30 Apr (PL) -- Today, a Cuban assembly 
committee reviewed a bill on citizenship, [word indistinct], 
loss, and recovery as a preamble to the special session the 
island's top legislative branch will begin tomorrow. 
  Ramon de la Cruz Ochoa, chairman of the Constitutional and 
Legal Affairs Committee of the National Assembly of the People's 
Government [ANPP], stressed the importance of the document under 
review, which paves the way for implementing of some of the 
agreements of the recently concluded meeting between the 
government and emigres. "The Nation and the Emigrants 
Conference," summoned by the Cuban Foreign Ministry, was held 
last weekend with the presence of more than 200 Cubans living 
abroad and broached many of those topics. 
  De la Cruz said citizenship constitutes the individual's 
legal and political link with the state and that it establishes 
reciprocal rights and obligations. He said the objective of the 
future law is [word indistinct], regulate the issuance of the 
appropriate documents that give proof of it. The analysis, which 
also served for a review of a bill on the organizing and 
functioning of the legislative branch, had [sentence incomplete 
as received]. 
  Another aspect the committee reviewed was the drafting of a 
bill on the principles and norms to bring in close association 
different cities of the world and their Cuban counterparts, a 
sign, in the lawmakers' opinion, of the growing solidarity with 
the Cuban cause. 
  Meanwhile, the Health, Sports, and Environment Committee 
centered its debates on the medicine control program that will 
be implemented soon. Public Health Minister Julio Teja voiced 
his optimism that the measures adopted tomorrow will alleviate 
the current shortage of certain medicines and meet the people's 
needs. 
  The Education, Culture, Science, and Technology Committee is 
devoting today's work [words indistinct] to outlining the 
self-financing system approved to guarantee the continuation of 
the activities of that sector. Abel Prieto, president of the 
Union of Writers and Artists, [sentence incomplete as received] 

</TEXT>

