<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Labor Court Head Appointed Labor Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Labor Court Head Appointed Labor Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0405012994 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0405012994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Luiz Augusto Mendonca from Planalto Palace] </F>
  [Text] Marcelo Pimentel, former Superior Labor Court, TST, 
president, is the new labor minister. This afternoon President 
Itamar Franco invited Marcelo Pimentel to head the Labor 
Ministry. Pimentel immediately accepted the position. 
  Marcelo Pimentel stood out in the TST for his frank dialogue 
with workers when decisions had to be made about collective 
bargaining accords, and as TST president. 
  Pimentel possesses all qualities President Franco wants in a 
labor minister. Franco wanted the labor minister to be well 
accepted by all labor unions. He will replace Mozart de Abreu 
Lima, who has been acting labor minister since Walter Barelli 
resigned to run in this year's general elections. 
  The date for Pimentel's installation as the new labor 
minister has yet to be set. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56458 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat086_n_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-086 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cooperation Program With Cuba Announced </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cooperation Program With Cuba Announced </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0405012094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1750 GMT 3 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0405012094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 3 May (EFE) -- Planning and Coordination 
Minister Luis Maira announced today that the Chilean Government 
will establish a cooperation program with Cuba and other 
Caribbean countries. 
  Participating in a seminar on strategic planning in 
international cooperation, Maira labeled such a program an 
"urgent need" despite the fact that from the political viewpoint 
the Chilean Government does not have among its short-term 
priorities the reestablishment of diplomatic relations with the 
Fidel Castro regime. 
  Bilateral links were broken in 1973 after the military coup 
headed by General Augusto Pinochet, who overthrew the socialist 
government of Salvador Allende. 
  Relations were resumed at the consular level in 1990, after 
the installation of the Patricio Aylwin administration. 
  Maira said that Chile, after surpassing the $3,000 per 
capita 
income level, has been excluded from the industrialized 
countries' financial cooperation aid list, and has entered a 
stage of transition from receptor to provider of this type of 
aid. 
  He said that within this context, Chile is beginning to be 
seen, especially in Central America and the Caribbean, as "a 
rich country." This has created a growing demand from that 
region for cooperation aid, which should somehow be arranged 
"despite the budget limits and restrictions" affecting the 
country. 
  "It is difficult to avoid these demands," said Maira, who 
added that the demands come mainly from Cuban and the Dominican 
Republic. 
  Maira said that in the case of Cuba it is necessary to have 
a 
growing degree of cooperation "on the basis of the progress and 
internal situation of Cuba and the presence on the island of 
several private Chilean companies." 
  Maira added that Chile is one of the Latin American 
countries 
with the largest investment programs abroad, especially in the 
region, and this should be taken into consideration in the 
government's action. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

