<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0305193794 </F>
<F P=103> PA0305193794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Venezuelan economic developments monitored through 3 
May. 
  Finexpo (Venezuelan Fund for Export Financing) has reported 
the credits it has granted, through financial institutions in 
the importing countries, have had a substantial increase in the 
first three months of the year. It financed 113 export 
operations between January and March 1994, versus 75 in the same 
period last year. The amount of credits also increased by more 
than $11 million from January to March 1993 to almost $22 
million during the same period of 1994. The lines of credit have 
been used primarily by financial institutions in Ecuador (9), 
Colombia (22), Peru (7), Chile (4), Bolivia (2), Argentina (2), 
Mexico (3), and Paraguay (2). Finexpo Vice President Policarpo 
Rodriguez has asserted he is still waiting for the Venezuelan 
Investment Fund to approve a new line of credit for $90 million, 
$80 million to be allotted to mid- and long-term operations and 
$10 million to the Fund for the Special Political Risk 
Insurance. (Caracas REPORTE DE LA ECONOMIA in Spanish 29 Apr 94 
p 20) 
  Norys Aguirre, the newly appointed president of the Deposit 
Guarantee and Banking Protection Fund (Fogade) has met with 
economic media representatives for the first time today and told 
them the public credit law will be the legal instrument to 
obtain the necessary economic resources to recapitalize the 
private banks subsidized by Fogade. (Caracas Radio Nacional de 
Venezuela Canal Clasico Network in Spanish 2200 GMT 28 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

