<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cavallo Views U.S. `Greatest Trade Pirates' Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cavallo Views U.S. `Greatest Trade Pirates' Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0305183494 Buenos Aires CLARIN in Spanish 2 May 94 p 23 </F>
<F P=103> PY0305183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires CLARIN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Upon learning through CLARIN of [U.S. Trade 
Representative] Mickey Kantor's latest remarks, Economy Minister 
Domingo Cavallo sought a favorable aspect from the threat. 
Cavallo said: "U.S. Ambassador James Cheek told President Menem 
that President Clinton has decided not to include Argentina for 
the next 60 days on the list of countries that are likely be 
punished. Kantor informed me over the telephone of this 
decision." 
  Cavallo noted: "The news is not that we will be punished; 
the 
news is that any possible punishments will not begin on 30 
April, the move has been moved back by at least 60 days. This 
represents a positive, not a negative gesture towards Argentina." 
  Concerning the harsh description of "greatest trade 
pirates," 
the minister noted: "Countries that do not protect intellectual 
property are involved in a type of piracy. We must not be 
offended by these words." 

</TEXT>

