<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas Vows To Defend Law, Accepts Rights Award </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas Vows To Defend Law, Accepts Rights Award </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0505004594 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 3 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0505004594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today, the Mexican president said his government is 
duty-bound to guarantee that the law prevails. Democracy and 
law go together and cannot be separated, President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari said at Los Pinos presidential residence when 
he received the 1994 Norma Corona Sapiens Award, granted by the 
Association of Litigant Lawyers of Mexico for the Defense of 
Human Rights. 
  Salinas was decorated with the national award named after 
Norma Corona Sapiens, a lawyer from Sinaloa who defended human 
rights and who was murdered during her struggle against drug 
traffickers associated with policemen. As a result of her 
murder, President Salinas created the National Human Rights 
Commission, which he later incorporated into the Constitution. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] My government has assigned top 
priority to the defense of human rights under all circumstances 
and with all due authority. I have pledged to guarantee rule of 
law. [end recording] 
  Even though he admitted there is much more to be done, the 
president said Mexico's legal system is at the vanguard of this 
century. 
  [Begin Salinas recording] Fighting against criminal bands, 
particularly those of drug traffickers, is indispensable for 
guaranteeing the civilized coexistence of society. [end 
recording] 
  Maximo Carvajal, dean of the School of Law of the Autonomous 
University of Mexico, said the award was given to President 
Salinas for his work in defending human rights in Mexico. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

