<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Briefs Frei on Talks With Kantor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Briefs Frei on Talks With Kantor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0405230794 Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen 
Internacional in Spanish 1800 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0405230794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen 
Internacional </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] After returning from the United States, Finance 
Minister Eduardo Aninat said today that Chile hopes to sign a 
free trade agreement with the United States by March 1995. 
  This comment was made by Aninat after meeting with President 
Eduardo Frei at La Moneda at noon today. Aninat, who arrived 
back in Chile early this morning, met with President Frei to 
brief him on the results of his trip. In Washington Aninat met 
with U.S. Trade Representative Michael Kantor, and the two 
agreed to start preliminary negotiations on 25 May, prior to 
beginning formal negotiations on a free trade agreement. 
  [Begin Aninat recording] We will not sign just any pact. We 
will sign a pact that is very rational, very coherent, in line 
with our economic policy, and suitable for Chile. In addition, 
before signing a pact we would discuss it with the political 
parties and, of course, with Congress. [end recording] 
  Aninat said that Chile has not yet decided whether to 
negotiate a bilateral agreement with the United States or to 
join NAFTA, which is also made up of Mexico and Canada. The 
importance of a free trade agreement with the United States lies 
in the fact that one-third of Chile's international trade is 
currently with the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

