<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Narcotics Chief Refutes De Greiff's Assessment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Narcotics Chief Refutes De Greiff's Assessment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0405193394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0405193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"; passages within quotation </F>
marks are recorded] 
  [Text] Point by point, the authorities involved in the drug 
fight refuted the prosecutor general's assessments. 
  [Colonel Jose Antonio Gallego, chief of the Narcotics 
Division] "I personally and professionally respect all 
observations made by the prosecutor general, but I cannot share 
that statement because it is very obvious that following the 
death of Gonzalo Rodiguez Gacha and Pablo Escobar, drug 
trafficking in Colombia was completely reduced to zero by the 
national government." 
  As for the increase in the amount of cultivated areas: 
  [Gallego] "That is not completely true because, as regards 
coca plantations, we have seen an increase since last year that 
is not more than 5 or 7 percent. The same is not true for 
marijuana or poppy plantations." 
  As for the small number of drug and money confiscations: 
  [Gallego] "We can say that we have confiscated plenty of 
drugs of different types in the country." 
  As for the small number of drug traffickers in jail: 
  [Gallego] "The National Police, alone, in the first four 
months of 1994, have arrested 450 Colombians and 42 foreigners 
involved in the trafficking of drugs." 
  As for the increase in drug consumption: 
  [Gallego] "An increase in consumption is relative. If it is 
indeed happening, it should not be in significant numbers 
because indicators show that, at this time, there is less 
availability of the substance than in previous years." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

