<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   FSLN Economist Supports Compensation Bonds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FSLN Economist Supports Compensation Bonds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20705C </F>
<F P=103> 94P20705C </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
CSO 

    [Editorial Report] Managua BARRICADA in Spanish of 19 April 
1994 reports on page 10 Sandinist National Liberation Front 
(FSLN) economist Alejandro Martinez Cuenca says in a commentary 
that compensation of former owners is the key to resolving the 
property issue. To this end, Martinez calls on the government 
"to act immediately to guarantee that more than 600-million 
cordobas paid out as bonds to former property owners retain 
their value." He suggests that the use of compensation bonds be 
expanded to include transactions taking place at state-owned 
banks, the customs office, and the income tax directorate. Bonds 
should also be used to complete the acquisition of shares for 
properties privatized by the National Corporation of the Public 
Sector begun in 1990. Martinez says that the government "should 
not delay taking action to guarantee the value of the 
compensation bonds." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

