<H3> <TI>   Nontraditional Product Joins Exports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nontraditional Product Joins Exports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20705D </F>
<F P=103> 94P20705D </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
CSO 

    [Editorial Report] Managua LA PRENSA in Spanish of 19 April 
1994 on page 4 reports that 800,000 pounds of chile tabasco 
peppers have been exported to the United States since the end of 
1993. The peppers, which are grown in Nueva Guinea, El Tuma, and 
farms in the western zone are sold at 30 cents per pound. 
Growers receive financing from the Nicaraguan Investment Fund 
and the National Development Bank. Exporter David Robleto 
explains that the peppers require no special handling for 
export. 

</TEXT>

