<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Maintains Firm Stand on Torricelli Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Maintains Firm Stand on Torricelli Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0505014494 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0505014494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 3 May, during an unusual news conference that 
linked him with reporters in several parts of the world, U.S. 
President Bill Clinton upheld his position of not varying on the 
U.S. policy toward Cuba. In response to a question by a Cuban 
television journalist, Clinton reiterated his support of the 
Torricelli Law and stressed that he does not expect any change 
in that policy for now. 
  President Clinton, who has been labeled as indecisive, at 
another point in the news conference, acknowledged that the 
United States is incapable of solving the problems of the world 
and [words indistinct] only when U.S. vital interests are 
endangered. 
  Regarding Haiti, Clinton warned that he has not dismissed 
the 
use of force and insisted that the DPRK must allow full 
inspection of its nuclear program. However, he was less 
aggressive regarding Bosnia when he affirmed that Washington's 
goal continues to be a negotiated peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

