<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sandinist Youth Express Disillusion With Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sandinist Youth Express Disillusion With Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20717A </F>
<F P=103> 94P20717A </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
CSO 

    [Editorial Report] Managua BARRTCADA in Spanish of 20 April 
1994 on pages 1 and 5 reports that Sandinist Youth (JS) members 
charge that the Sandinist National Liberation Front (FSLN) is 
"divorced" from its youth members. In addition to the accusation 
that the FSLN "is turning into a party for the old," JS members 
say the party suffers from a lack of unity and democracy and 
"has lost credibility...due to the behavior of its leaders." 
Former JS leader Roberto Stuart points out that the party is no 
longer influential with young people because FSLN leaders "do 
not listen" to the ideas of others. Javier Cardoze, JS secretary 
in Rivas, warns that the FSLN will be hard pressed "to attract 
the youth vote in 1996." Youth leaders call for wider 
participation by JS members in decisionmaking activities and a 
higher standard of ethics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

