<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papa Egoro Leader Denies Ties With Communists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papa Egoro Leader Denies Ties With Communists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0605004494 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0605004494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Ricardo Ledezma, a member of Ruben Blades' campaign 
committee, has stressed that the leadership of the Papa Egoro 
Movement [MPE] is not under communist influence, nor does it 
maintain any type of relationship with Fidel Castro's Cuban 
Government. 
  Leo Gonzalez, a legislator for Molirena [Nationalist Liberal 
Republican Movement] stated that Fidel Castro's regime is 
allegedly coordinating and providing logistical support for 
members of the PRD [Democratic Revolutionary Party] and PRD 
dissidents who joined the MPE. Gonzalez says he has sent 
documents attesting to this to Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino 
for verification and for an investigation. Thus far, the 
Foreign Ministry has said nothing. 
  Meanwhile, Ricardo Ledezma said the accusations are 
unfounded. 
  [Begin recording] [Ledezma] An accusation is filed when 
there is proof to confirm the accusation. We believe these 
accusations are irresponsible, particularly in the final stages 
of the electoral period. We are in the final week of an 
electoral period that has been rather calm. It is dangerous to 
make accusations like these without clear evidence. 
  [Unidentified reporter] MPE has not had contact with Cuba or 
any Cubans during this election? 
  [Ledezma, laughing] No, there has been no contact. I have a 
couple of Cuban friends who have resided in Panama for many 
years. 
  [Reporter] Mr. Ledezma, there have been reports suggesting 
that the Italian Communist Party's flag is very similar to the 
MPE's. 
  [Ledezma] That is another example of manipulation. It is 
obvious this is a campaign orchestrated by the traditional 
political parties to prevent the triumph of decency in these 
elections. That is obvious. These matters are highly 
manipulated. Take for example the flag issue; the fact there 
are trees in the Communist Party's flag and our flag is 
insignificant. It is as if I took the flag of any other 
political party and associated it with 1,000 symbols that exist 
in this world only because they have the same colors or similar 
elements. In other words, this is so childish that the people 
can clearly see it is a smear campaign. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56601 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat088_j_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0505212794 </F>
<F P=103> PA0505212794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Panamanian elections 
scheduled for 8 May 1994. 
  Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, presidential candidate for the 
Arnulfist Party (PA), said on 26 April that the constitutional 
articles on the creation and functions of the defunct Panama 
Defense Forces must be amended. De Gruber visited Betania 
Corregimiento on the morning of 26 April and stated: "When the 
president tried to reform the Constitution, various legislators 
erroneously tried to modify several articles. That is why the 
Panamanian people rejected the constitutional reforms." (Panama 
City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 26 Apr 94) 
  Ruben Blades, presidential candidate of the Papa Egoro 
Movement, MPE, said that the polls indicate he is tied for first 
place with Democratic Revolutionary Party, PRD, candidate 
Ernesto Perez Balladares. Regarding support for him in the 
interior, Blades stated: "I think we have more support in the 
interior than is reflected in the polls." MPE slate members 
said as part of their government program that no public 
employees will be dismissed. (Panama City Circuito RPC 
Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 28 Apr 94) 
  Government Minister Jacobo Salas said that the president 
guaranteed that the 8 May elections will be free. Salas 
explained that "violence will not be tolerated, regardless of 
where it comes from." Regarding the decree banning weapons 
sales, Salas said it will remain in effect until 31 March. The 
minister stressed that "it is the president's desire to hold 
free elections in which violence -- we are confident there will 
not be any violence -- must be repressed, regardless of where it 
originates." (Panama City EL SIGLO in Spanish 28 Apr 94 p 10) 
  Transportation sectors have endorsed the Democratic Alliance 
slate led by Mireya Moscoso de Gruber. Some 52 taxi drivers' 
organizations in Panama Province met in a Panama City hotel to 
endorse the candidacy of PA presidential candidate Mireya 
Moscoso de Gruber. The transportation workers delivered Mrs. De 
Gruber a list of proposals to modify Law 14 regulating 
transportation. De Gruber promised to meet the transportation 
workers' requests and said: "When we are at the presidency, you 
will have a friend more than a president. You will advise me on 
how my government can work better for all of you." (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 29 Apr 94) 
  On the evening of 3 May, PRD presidential candidate Ernesto 
Perez Balladares met with farmers from Chiriqui Province in 
Boquete. Perez Balladares addressed farmers on the need to 
improve roads in production areas, erroneous government 
agricultural policy, and falling coffee prices. He told 
producers he will establish "adequate protection for the 
agricultural sector for crops such as potatoes, rice, beans, 
corn, and sorghum." (Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA 5 May 94 
p B7) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

