<H3> <TI>   Government Supports Tucuman Governor Ortega </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Supports Tucuman Governor Ortega </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505192794 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1228 GMT 4 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0505192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 4 May (NA) -- Reliable official 
sources have indicated that, during a meeting with Economy 
Minister Domingo Cavallo and Presidential Secretary General 
Eduardo Bauza, Tucuman Governor Ramon "Palito" Ortega allegedly 
tendered his resignation due to serious disagreements between 
him and the ruling-party's bloc in the provincial congress. 
  Government officials calmed the provincial governor, 
confirming their support for his government actions and 
promising that they would seek a solution to the crisis as last 
night similar reports noted that top-level government circles 
were drawing up a decree on the intervention of the Tucuman 
congress. 
  Official sources unofficially reported that Justicialist 
Party [PJ] provincial legislators have been urgently summoned to 
the federal capital to meet government officials within the next 
few hours at Government House to seek a "political solution" 
before implementing a federal solution. 
  Ortega yesterday received the support of President Carlos 
Menem and that of his high-ranking government officials over the 
"worrisome" opposition to his actions by the Tucuman PJ deputies. 
  Menem said: "We shall see what can be done, but the people 
have elected them to legislate and not to block the actions of 
those who are governing, as is happening in Tucuman." 
  Strongly supporting Ortega, Menem challenged: "It seems the 
vice governor Julio Diaz Lozano very strongly opposes the 
governor." 

</TEXT>

