<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Condemns U.S. Subsidies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Condemns U.S. Subsidies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0605000394 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 5 May 94 p 
26 </F>

<F P=103> PY0605000394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary: "Trade Ethics"] </F>
  [Text] President Bill Clinton is correct in promoting 
exports, which are responsible for 80 percent of U.S. economic 
growth and also for more than 12 million direct jobs. 
  But as a world trade leader and defender of ethical, free, 
and fair competition in international trade, the United States 
should be the first to observe the rules, and set an example of 
what it preaches. 
  Following the donation of $800 per ton of frozen chicken 
exported to Arab countries, the U.S. Government has now decided 
to grant a bonus, within the same system of subsidies (Export 
Enhancement Program), of $47 per ton to help sell 798,000 tons 
of wheat to the PRC. 
  The United States thus has no authority to demand within the 
GATT/World Trade Organization that developing countries (like 
Brazil, India, etc.) be condemned for "social dumping" for 
having lower salaries in their export production sectors than do 
the industrialized countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

