<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505212094 </F>
<F P=103> PY0505212094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 5 May. 
  Energy Minister Alexis Stepanenko on 29 April announced that 
Petrobras -- Brazilian Petroleum Corporation -- may no longer 
pass on the cost of oil importation taxes to consumers in the 
price of fuel. The taxes affect the importation of oil and 
by-products. Petrobras has so far paid a 38 percent tax on crude 
oil imports, which was passed on to consumers in the form of 
higher fuel prices. The corporation will now have to absorb the 
cost of this tax. (Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 30 Apr 
94 p 1) 
  The Institute of Nonferrous Metals has reported that in the 
first quarter of 1994 the production of nickel stood at 3,491 
tonnes, and that during the same period in 1993 nickel 
production stood at 3,915 tonnes. These figures show that 
during the first quarter of 1994 Brazilian nickel production 
dropped by 10.82 percent with respect to the same period in 
1993. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 3 May 94 p 14) 
  The last stage of the privatization of the National Iron and 
Steel Company -- CSN -- was concluded during the week ending 23 
April. The shares that still had to be sold, amounting to 9 
percent of the enterprise's capital, were sold in two auctions 
conducted in March and last week. The operation yielded $1.494 
billion. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 28 Apr 
94 p B4) 
  The average general price index stood at 40.91 percent in 
April. This figure stands almost 5 percentage points below the 
45.7 percent rate that was registered in March. (Sao Paulo O 
ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 1 May 94 p A14) 
  Professor Roberto Cavalcanti, of the National Institute for 
Advanced Studies, on 27 April submitted a research paper 
reporting that there are 39.2 million poor people in Brazil, of 
whom 21.7 million are in the northeastern region, and that there 
are 3.1 million poor people in the three southeastern 
metropolitan regions -- Sao Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Belo 
Horizonte. Cavalcanti considered poor the members of a family 
whose monthly per capita income stood below $35, in values that 
were in force in 1990. (Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 28 Apr 94 p 10) 
  The balance of trade registered a $1.03 billion surplus in 
March. This figure is 31.97 percent lower than the figure 
registered in March 1993. Ailton Barcellos, executive secretary 
of the Ministry of Industry and Commerce, on 27 April reported 
that exports in March 1994 -- which stood at $3.351 billion -- 
dropped by 4.67 percent with respect to March 1993. Imports, 
which stood at $2.321 billion in March 1994, grew by 15.99 
percent. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 28 Apr 
94 p B7) 
  On 29 April Petrobras began operating the 1,027 meter deep 
Marlim-4 oil well in Campos Basin, off the coast of Rio de 
Janeiro. This is Petrobras' deepest underwater oil well. The 
well is part of the Marlim Sur Master Project, in which $34 
million has been invested. Marlim-4 will produce 6,300 barrels 
per day at a cost of $3.45 per barrel. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 2 May 94 p 13) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

