<H3> <TI>   Air Force Studies Introduction of Russian Technology </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Air Force Studies Introduction of Russian Technology </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0605040094 Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 30 Apr 94 p C2 </F>
<F P=103> PY0605040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago EL MERCURIO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] General Ramon Vega Hidalgo, commander in chief of 
the Chilean Air Force [FACh], has said the institution is 
analyzing Russian aerospace technology and will possibly 
introduce it into the systems it currently possesses. 
  He pointed out that "together with the Russians, we are 
evaluating the possibility of introducing their technology into 
our national systems, and then establishing programs with them." 
He explained that it is a slow process. 
  Gen. Vega reported that for many years the FACh has been 
working on concrete technological programs with U.S. academies 
and universities, and training engineers in electronics, 
communications, and computing, as well as creating new systems 
for the institution. 
  At noon yesterday, the FACh commander in chief granted an 
interview to the media at the end of a ceremony celebrating the 
57th anniversary of the Air War Academy. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

