<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-088 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505211094 </F>
<F P=103> PY0505211094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 5 May. 
  The Central Bank reported that the public sector's foreign 
debt was $19.628 billion through February, of which 64.4 percent 
corresponds to the nonfinancial sector and 25.5 percent to the 
financial institutions. The private sector's debt totalled 
$10.513 billion. (Santiago ESTRATEGIA in Spanish 13 Apr 94 p 7) 
  Budget Director Jose Pablo Arellano said public expenditure 
increased by almost 7 percent in 1993, with savings being 5 
percent of the GDP. He also said social expenses grew 9.5 
percent, and public investment 20 percent. (Santiago ESTRATEGIA 
in Spanish 21 Apr 94 Economic Section p 4) 
  Economy Minister Alvaro Garcia reported that foreign 
investment totalled $804.9 million in the year's first quarter, 
19 percent higher than in the same period of 1993. Mining 
received the highest percentage of the investment, with 66 
percent; services 20.9 percent; industry 7.1 percent; 
construction 2.9 percent; and agriculture 1.5 percent. 
(Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 21 Apr 94 pp B1-B12) 
  The Central Bank reported that the trade balance registered 
a 
$135 million surplus in the year's first quarter as compared 
with the $75.5 million deficit registered during the same period 
in 1993. Exports totalled $2.5254 billion and imports $2.3904 
billion. (Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 26 Apr 94 pp B1-B6) 
  On 3 May, the Comptroller General's Office established a new 
telephone tariff system which entails a 21 percent reduction in 
fixed monthly rates. This measure will particularly benefit 
those people living in areas surrounding large urban centers. 
(Madrid EFE in Spanish 2319 GMT 3 May 94) 

</TEXT>

