<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `To Withdraw' From Mercosur Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government `To Withdraw' From Mercosur Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505170194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1250 GMT 5 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0505170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 5 May (EFE) -- The Uruguayan Government 
has decided to unilaterally withdraw from negotiations to 
establish a Common Market of the South [Mercosur] common 
external tariff until Brazil, the largest Mercosur member 
country, clarifies the terms of its proposal to create a 
continental free trade zone. 
  Official sources advised the press of the decision today. 
The decision was made by President Luis Alberto Lacalle at the 
suggestion of Economy and Finance Minister Ignacio de Posadas. 
  The minister argued that Uruguay must pay dearly for 
maintaining a very high external tariff and cannot permit other 
countries in the region to use the American free trade zone to 
allow products into Brazil "at a significantly lower cost." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

