<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505220394 </F>
<F P=103> PY0505220394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 5 
May. 
  The construction industry continued to enjoy a boom during 
the first quarter of the year, as shown by increased sales of 
Portland cement for public and private construction, which grew 
by 80 and 11 percent respectively. Sales of gas oil and fuel oil 
dropped by 24 and 56 percent respectively in the first quarter. 
This is an indication of the recession that has been affecting 
the Uruguayan industry for over a year. A 4.3 percent drop in 
the volume of milk processed at pasteurizing plants was also 
registered in the said quarter. There has been an upturn in 
livestock activities during this quarter, as wool exports grew 
by 27 percent and the number of cattle slaughtered increased by 
13.4 percent. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR in Spanish 21 Apr 94 p 9) 
  The executive branch decreed an average 9 percent increase 
in 
gasoline prices. The measure entered into effect at 0000 on 27 
April. (Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 27 Apr 94 p 1) 
  According to Uruguay's Merchant Products Chamber, the 
country 
exported 32.5 percent more wool during the period October 
1993-March 1994 than during a similar period last year. The 
country exported a total of 64,139 tonnes of wool, expressed in 
terms of dirty wool. Of this total the equivalent of 10,863 
tonnes was washed wool while 39,482 tonnes was industrialized 
wool. The main importers of dirty wool were the United Kingdom, 
the PRC, the Netherlands, Colombia, and the United States. The 
main purchasers of washed wool were Germany, Italy, the PRC, and 
the United States, and the main purchasers of industrialized 
wool were the PRC, Italy, Germany, and Hong Kong. (Montevideo EL 
PAIS 26 Apr 94 p 1) 
  There are two indicators of the good liquidity in the 
financial system at present. One is the considerable amount of 
overnight money deposited at the Central Bank on 25 
April--337.5479 million pesos, at an annual rate of 29 percent. 
The second is the great influx of money in the biddings for 
Treasury bills in pesos with a 63-day maturity, which exceeds 
100 million pesos every week. Interbank call money rates have 
also suffered the consequences of good liquidity, dropping to 31 
percent annually. (Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 26 Apr 94 
Market Indicators Section p 1) 
  The National Statistics Institute has reported that the 
unemployment rate in Montevideo dropped by nearly 1 percent in 
the first quarter of the year as compared with the corresponding 
period last year. It stood at 8.1 percent. This figure, however, 
does not represent a decrease in the number of people 
unemployed, but rather a decline in the working population. The 
retail sector is the most severely hit by unemployment, with 7.8 
percent, followed by industry with a 7.5 percent unemployment 
rate. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 27 Apr 94 p 
7) 
  Construction costs were up by 7.1 percent in March, thus 
registering a 9.5 percent increase so far this year. Over the 
last 12 months costs have edged up by 51.6 percent. (Montevideo 
EL PAIS in Spanish 27 Apr 94 Market Indicators Section p 1) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

