<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   MNP-28 Accuses Clinton of Violating Sovereignty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MNP-28 Accuses Clinton of Violating Sovereignty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0605231594 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1600 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0605231594 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] MNP-28 [National Patriotic Movement of 28 November], 
led by Dejean Belizaire, reacted to the threats of military 
intervention in Haiti and the total embargo planned against 
Haiti. Belizaire accuses the U.S. President of violating the 
national sovereignty of the Republic of Haiti. The former 
president of the National Assembly condemns the behavior of the 
international community, which is trying, he says, to impose a 
solution from the outside to a crisis that is above all, 
Haitian. It is up to Haitians to solve the problems of power and 
of the political regime in Haiti, stated Belizaire on this new 
twist in the political crisis: 
  [Begin Belizaire recording] Haiti is an independent, 
sovereign state, bound through mutual respect to cooperate with 
the other states in the hemisphere and with the international 
institutions. But it is up to Haitians and to Haitians alone to 
solve the problems of power and political regimes in this 
country. It is desirable under the exceptional circumstances of 
this crisis, however, that the opposing parties understand that 
in their search for a durable solution, they must be open to 
mutual concessions or to pay an unavoidable price. 
  Second, the institution of democracy in Haiti, as is the 
case 
for all countries in the hemisphere, will be the product of the 
economic, political, and social contradiction game, and of a 
long process. But it cannot in any way be imposed from the 
outside. The 19 years of U.S. military occupation, beginning in 
1915, only broke the dynamic struggle of the Haitian people for 
change, and interrupted the country's process of democratization. 
  Third, a total and complete embargo and military invasion as 
a means of solving the Haitian crisis is a monumental, gross 
mistake from which the international community must immediately 
dissociate in order to safeguard its distinguished image and the 
future of its relations with the Haitian people and with the 
authentic political parties, the only ones that are permanent, 
durable, and unfailingly attached to the fate of the sovereign 
Republic of Haiti. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56663 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat089_b_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   MRN Leader Ends Silence, Demands Cedras Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MRN Leader Ends Silence, Demands Cedras Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0605202194 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0605202194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks in Creole] </F>
  [Excerpts] The National Reconstruction Movement [MRN] of 
Rene Theodore has demanded the resignation of General Raoul 
Cedras as a way out of the deadlock. MRN leader Rene Theodore, 
former prospective prime minister, explained in a statement on 
Signal FM that the departure of Gen. Raoul Cedras is necessary 
to avoid a military intervention in Port-au-Prince: 
  [Begin Theodore recording] "Instead of speaking of military 
intervention, since the Haitian military institution is not 
hostile toward anyone, the foreign powers should carry out their 
commitment to bring military cooperation to Haiti to help 
discipline the Haitian Army, professionalize the officers and 
noncommissioned officers of the Haitian Army, and establish the 
police force provided for by the Haitian Constitution. They 
signed documents to this effect and they must fulfill their 
obligation." [end recording] 
  Theodore also calls on the sectors involved in the crisis to 
work toward a respect for legality and legitimacy. MRN demands 
the return of President Jean-Bertrand Aristide to avoid the 
reinforcement of sanctions against the country. Theodore reminds 
parliamentarians of the difficult crossroads the country is 
facing: 
  [Begin Theodore recording] "[Passage omitted] It is very 
clear to everyone that the resolution of the crisis will begin 
with the resignation of Gen. Cedras. MRN demands the resignation 
of Gen. Cedras as the first step toward cancellation of the 
international community's actions and claims." [end recording] 
  This was Rene Theodore who has ended his silence, his long 
silence, to take a stand in favor of the return of President 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

